# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: jackknife-resampling
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:jackknife-resampling/bias-of-an-estimator] In statistics, the **bias of an estimator** (or **bias function**) is the difference between this estimator's expected value and the true value of the parameter being estimated.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bias-of-an-estimator] An estimator or decision rule with zero bias is called ***unbiased***.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bias-of-an-estimator] In statistics, "bias" is an *objective* property of an estimator.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bias-of-an-estimator] Bias is a distinct concept from consistency: consistent estimators converge in probability to the true value of the parameter, but may be biased or unbiased (see bias versus consistency for more).
[src:jackknife-resampling/bias-of-an-estimator] All else being equal, an unbiased estimator is preferable to a biased estimator, although in practice, biased estimators (with generally small bias) are frequently used.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bias-of-an-estimator] When a biased estimator is used, bounds of the bias are calculated.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bias-of-an-estimator] Bias can also be measured with respect to the median, rather than the mean (expected value), in which case one distinguishes *median*-unbiased from the usual *mean*-unbiasedness property.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bias-of-an-estimator] Mean-unbiasedness is not preserved under non-linear transformations, though median-unbiasedness is (see § Effect of transformations); for example, the sample variance is a biased estimator for the population variance.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bias-of-an-estimator] An unbiased estimator for a parameter need not always exist.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bias-of-an-estimator] For example, there is no unbiased estimator for the reciprocal of the parameter of a binomial random variable.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bias-of-an-estimator] Suppose we have a statistical model, parameterized by a real number *θ*, giving rise to a probability distribution for observed data, $P_{\theta }(x)=P(x\mid \theta )$ , and a statistic ${\hat {\theta }}$ which serves as an estimator of *θ* based on any observed data x .
[src:jackknife-resampling/bias-of-an-estimator] That is, we assume that our data follows some unknown distribution $P(x\mid \theta )$ (where *θ* is a fixed, unknown constant that is part of this distribution), and then we construct some estimator ${\hat {\theta }}$ that maps observed data to values that we hope are close to *θ*.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bias-of-an-estimator] where $\operatorname {E} _{x\mid \theta }$ denotes expected value over the distribution $P(x\mid \theta )$ (i.e., averaging over all possible observations x ).
[src:jackknife-resampling/bias-of-an-estimator] The second equation follows since *θ* is measurable with respect to the conditional distribution $P(x\mid \theta )$ .
[src:jackknife-resampling/bias-of-an-estimator] An estimator is said to be **unbiased** if its bias is zero for all values of the parameter *θ*, or equivalently, if the expected value of the estimator matches that of the parameter.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bias-of-an-estimator] Unbiasedness is not guaranteed to carry over.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bias-of-an-estimator] For example, if ${\hat {\theta }}$ is an unbiased estimator for parameter *θ*, it is not guaranteed in general that g( ${\hat {\theta }}$ ) is an unbiased estimator for *g(θ)*, unless *g* is a linear function.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bias-of-an-estimator] In a simulation experiment concerning the properties of an estimator, the bias of the estimator may be assessed using the mean signed difference.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bias-of-an-estimator] The sample variance highlights two different issues about bias and risk.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bias-of-an-estimator] First, the “naive” estimator that divides by *n* is biased downward because the sample mean is estimated from the same data.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bias-of-an-estimator] Multiplying by *n/(n−1)* (Bessel’s correction) yields an unbiased estimator.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bias-of-an-estimator] Second, unbiasedness does not imply minimum mean squared error.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bias-of-an-estimator] Suppose *X*1, ..., *X**n* are independent and identically distributed (i.i.d.) random variables with expectation *μ* and variance *σ*2.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bias-of-an-estimator] then *S*2 is a biased estimator of *σ*2.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bias-of-an-estimator] In other words, the expected value of the uncorrected sample variance does not equal the population variance *σ*2, unless multiplied by a normalization factor.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bias-of-an-estimator] The ratio between the biased (uncorrected) and unbiased estimates of the variance is known as Bessel's correction.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bias-of-an-estimator] The sample mean, on the other hand, is an unbiased estimator of the population mean *μ*.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bias-of-an-estimator] The reason that an uncorrected sample variance, *S*2, is biased stems from the fact that the sample mean is an ordinary least squares (OLS) estimator for *μ*: ${\overline {X}}$ is the number that makes the sum ${\textstyle \sum _{i=1}^{n}(X_{i}-{\overline {X}})^{2}}$ as small as possible.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bias-of-an-estimator] That is, when any other number is plugged into this sum, the sum can only increase.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bias-of-an-estimator] The above discussion can be understood in geometric terms: the vector ${\vec {C}}=(X_{1}-\mu ,\ldots ,X_{n}-\mu )$ can be decomposed into the "mean part" and "variance part" by projecting to the direction of ${\vec {u}}=(1,\ldots ,1)$ and to that direction's orthogonal complement hyperplane.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bias-of-an-estimator] This is in fact true in general, as explained above.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bias-of-an-estimator] A far more extreme case of a biased estimator being better than any unbiased estimator arises from the Poisson distribution.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bias-of-an-estimator] Suppose that *X* has a Poisson distribution with expectation *λ*.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bias-of-an-estimator] To see this, note that when decomposing e−*λ* from the above expression for expectation, the sum that is left is a Taylor series expansion of e−*λ* as well, yielding e−*λ*e−*λ* = e−2*λ* (see Characterizations of the exponential function).
[src:jackknife-resampling/bias-of-an-estimator] If the observed value of *X* is 100, then the estimate is 1, although the true value of the quantity being estimated is very likely to be near 0, which is the opposite extreme.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bias-of-an-estimator] And, if *X* is observed to be 101, then the estimate is even more absurd: It is −1, although the quantity being estimated must be positive.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bias-of-an-estimator] is far better than this unbiased estimator.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bias-of-an-estimator] The MSEs are functions of the true value *λ*.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bias-of-an-estimator] The bias of maximum-likelihood estimators can be substantial.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bias-of-an-estimator] Consider a case where *n* tickets numbered from 1 to *n* are placed in a box and one is selected at random, giving a value *X*.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bias-of-an-estimator] If *n* is unknown, then the maximum-likelihood estimator of *n* is *X*, even though the expectation of *X* given *n* is only (*n* + 1)/2; we can be certain only that *n* is at least *X* and is probably more.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bias-of-an-estimator] In this case, the natural unbiased estimator is 2*X* − 1.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bias-of-an-estimator] The theory of median-unbiased estimators was revived by George W.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bias-of-an-estimator] Further properties of median-unbiased estimators have been noted by Lehmann, Birnbaum, van der Vaart and Pfanzagl.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bias-of-an-estimator] In particular, median-unbiased estimators exist in cases where mean-unbiased and maximum-likelihood estimators do not exist.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bias-of-an-estimator] They are invariant under one-to-one transformations.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bias-of-an-estimator] There are methods of construction median-unbiased estimators for probability distributions that have monotone likelihood-functions, such as one-parameter exponential families, to ensure that they are optimal (in a sense analogous to minimum-variance property considered for mean-unbiased estimators).
[src:jackknife-resampling/bias-of-an-estimator] One such procedure is an analogue of the Rao–Blackwell procedure for mean-unbiased estimators: The procedure holds for a smaller class of probability distributions than does the Rao–Blackwell procedure for mean-unbiased estimation but for a larger class of loss-functions.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bias-of-an-estimator] Any minimum-variance *mean*-unbiased estimator minimizes the risk (expected loss) with respect to the squared-error loss function (among mean-unbiased estimators), as observed by Gauss.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bias-of-an-estimator] A minimum-average absolute deviation *median*-unbiased estimator minimizes the risk with respect to the absolute loss function (among median-unbiased estimators), as observed by Laplace.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bias-of-an-estimator] Other loss functions are used in statistics, particularly in robust statistics.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bias-of-an-estimator] For univariate parameters, median-unbiased estimators remain median-unbiased under transformations that preserve order (or reverse order).
[src:jackknife-resampling/bias-of-an-estimator] Note that, when a transformation is applied to a mean-unbiased estimator, the result need not be a mean-unbiased estimator of its corresponding population statistic.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bias-of-an-estimator] By Jensen's inequality, a convex function as transformation will introduce positive bias, while a concave function will introduce negative bias, and a function of mixed convexity may introduce bias in either direction, depending on the specific function and distribution.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bias-of-an-estimator] That is, for a non-linear function *f* and a mean-unbiased estimator *U* of a parameter *p*, the composite estimator *f*(*U*) need not be a mean-unbiased estimator of *f*(*p*).
[src:jackknife-resampling/bias-of-an-estimator] For example, the square root of the unbiased estimator of the population variance is *not* a mean-unbiased estimator of the population standard deviation: the square root of the unbiased sample variance, the corrected sample standard deviation, is biased.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bias-of-an-estimator] The bias depends both on the sampling distribution of the estimator and on the transform, and can be quite involved to calculate – see unbiased estimation of standard deviation for a discussion in this case.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bias-of-an-estimator] While bias quantifies the *average* difference to be expected between an estimator and an underlying parameter, an estimator based on a finite sample can additionally be expected to differ from the parameter due to the randomness in the sample.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bias-of-an-estimator] An estimator that minimises the bias will not necessarily minimise the mean square error.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bias-of-an-estimator] With a little algebra it can be confirmed that it is *c* = 1/(*n* + 1) which minimises this combined loss function, rather than *c* = 1/(*n* − 1) which minimises just the square of the bias.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bias-of-an-estimator] More generally it is only in restricted classes of problems that there will be an estimator that minimises the MSE independently of the parameter values.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bias-of-an-estimator] However it is very common that there may be perceived to be a *bias–variance tradeoff*, such that a small increase in bias can be traded for a larger decrease in variance, resulting in a more desirable estimator overall.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bias-of-an-estimator] Most bayesians are rather unconcerned about unbiasedness (at least in the formal sampling-theory sense above) of their estimates.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bias-of-an-estimator] Fundamentally, the difference between the Bayesian approach and the sampling-theory approach above is that in the sampling-theory approach the parameter is taken as fixed, and then probability distributions of a statistic are considered, based on the predicted sampling distribution of the data.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bias-of-an-estimator] Here the second term, the likelihood of the data given the unknown parameter value θ, depends just on the data obtained and the modelling of the data generation process.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bias-of-an-estimator] However a Bayesian calculation also includes the first term, the prior probability for θ, which takes account of everything the analyst may know or suspect about θ *before* the data comes in.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bias-of-an-estimator] This information plays no part in the sampling-theory approach; indeed any attempt to include it would be considered "bias" away from what was pointed to purely by the data.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bias-of-an-estimator] To the extent that Bayesian calculations include prior information, it is therefore essentially inevitable that their results will not be "unbiased" in sampling theory terms.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bias-of-an-estimator] But the results of a Bayesian approach can differ from the sampling theory approach even if the Bayesian tries to adopt an "uninformative" prior.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bias-of-an-estimator] A standard choice of uninformative prior for this problem is the Jeffreys prior, $\scriptstyle {p(\sigma ^{2})\;\propto \;1/\sigma ^{2}}$ , which is equivalent to adopting a rescaling-invariant flat prior for **ln(σ2)**.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bias-of-an-estimator] — when the expectation is taken over the probability distribution of σ2 given *S*2, as it is in the Bayesian case, rather than *S*2 given σ2, one can no longer take σ4 as a constant and factor it out.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bias-of-an-estimator] The worked-out Bayesian calculation gives a scaled inverse chi-squared distribution with *n* − 1 degrees of freedom for the posterior probability distribution of σ2.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bias-of-an-estimator] The expected loss is minimised when *cnS*2 = <σ2>; this occurs when *c* = 1/(*n* − 3).
[src:jackknife-resampling/bias-of-an-estimator] Even with an uninformative prior, therefore, a Bayesian calculation may not give the same expected-loss minimising result as the corresponding sampling-theory calculation.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] Bootstrapping estimates the properties of an estimand (such as its variance) by measuring those properties when sampling from an approximating distribution.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] One standard choice for an approximating distribution is the empirical distribution function of the observed data.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] In the case where a set of observations can be assumed to be from an independent and identically distributed population, this can be implemented by constructing a number of resamples with replacement, of the observed data set (and of equal size to the observed data set).
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] A key result in Efron's seminal paper that introduced the bootstrap is the favorable performance of bootstrap methods using sampling with replacement compared to prior methods like the jackknife that sample without replacement.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] However, since its introduction, numerous variants on the bootstrap have been proposed, including methods that sample without replacement or that create bootstrap samples larger or smaller than the original data.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] The bootstrap may also be used for constructing hypothesis tests.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] It is often used as an alternative to statistical inference based on the assumption of a parametric model when that assumption is in doubt, or where parametric inference is impossible or requires complicated formulas for the calculation of standard errors.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] The bootstrap was first described by Bradley Efron in "Bootstrap methods: another look at the jackknife" (1979), inspired by earlier work on the jackknife.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] Improved estimates of the variance were developed later.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] A Bayesian extension was developed in 1981.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] The bias-corrected and accelerated ( $BC_{a}$ ) bootstrap was developed by Efron in 1987, and the approximate bootstrap confidence interval (ABC, or approximate $BC_{a}$ ) procedure in 1992.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] The basic idea of bootstrapping is that inference about a population from sample data (sample → population) can be modeled by *resampling* the sample data and performing inference about a sample from resampled data (resampled → sample).
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] As the population is unknown, the true error in a sample statistic against its population value is unknown.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] In bootstrap-resamples, the 'population' is in fact the sample, and this is known; hence the quality of inference of the 'true' sample from resampled data (resampled → sample) is measurable.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] More formally, the bootstrap works by treating inference of the true probability distribution *J*, given the original data, as being analogous to an inference of the empirical distribution *Ĵ*, given the resampled data.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] The accuracy of inferences regarding *Ĵ* using the resampled data can be assessed because we know *Ĵ*.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] If *Ĵ* is a reasonable approximation to *J*, then the quality of inference on *J* can in turn be inferred.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] As an example, assume we are interested in the average (or mean) height of people worldwide.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] We cannot measure all the people in the global population, so instead, we sample only a tiny part of it, and measure that.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] Assume the sample is of size *N*; that is, we measure the heights of *N* individuals.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] From that single sample, only one estimate of the mean can be obtained.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] In order to reason about the population, we need some sense of the variability of the mean that we have computed.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] The simplest bootstrap method involves taking the original data set of heights, and, using a computer, sampling from it to form a new sample (called a 'resample' or bootstrap sample) that is also of size *N*.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] This process is repeated a large number of times (typically 1,000 or 10,000 times), and for each of these bootstrap samples, we compute its mean (each of these is called a "bootstrap estimate").
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] We now can create a histogram of bootstrap means.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] This histogram provides an estimate of the shape of the distribution of the sample mean from which we can answer questions about how much the mean varies across samples.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] A great advantage of bootstrap is its simplicity.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] It is a straightforward way to derive estimates of standard errors and confidence intervals for complex estimators of the distribution, such as percentile points, proportions, Odds ratio, and correlation coefficients.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] However, despite its simplicity, bootstrapping can be applied to complex sampling designs (e.g. for population divided into s strata with ns observations per strata, one example of which is a dose-response experiment, where bootstrapping can be applied for each stratum).
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] Bootstrap is also an appropriate way to control and check the stability of the results.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] Although for most problems it is impossible to know the true confidence interval, bootstrap is asymptotically more accurate than the standard intervals obtained using sample variance and assumptions of normality.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] Bootstrapping is also a convenient method that avoids the cost of repeating the experiment to get other groups of sample data.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] Bootstrapping depends heavily on the estimator used and, though simple, naive use of bootstrapping will not always yield asymptotically valid results and can lead to inconsistency.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] Although bootstrapping is (under some conditions) asymptotically consistent, it does not provide general finite-sample guarantees.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] The result may depend on the representative sample.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] The apparent simplicity may conceal the fact that important assumptions are being made when undertaking the bootstrap analysis (e.g. independence of samples or large enough of a sample size) where these would be more formally stated in other approaches.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] Also, bootstrapping can be time-consuming and there are not many available software for bootstrapping as it is difficult to automate using traditional statistical computer packages.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] Scholars have recommended more bootstrap samples as available computing power has increased.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] If the results may have substantial real-world consequences, then one should use as many samples as is reasonable, given available computing power and time.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] Increasing the number of samples cannot increase the amount of information in the original data; it can only reduce the effects of random sampling errors which can arise from a bootstrap procedure itself.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] Moreover, there is evidence that numbers of samples greater than 100 lead to negligible improvements in the estimation of standard errors.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] In fact, according to the original developer of the bootstrapping method, even setting the number of samples at 50 is likely to lead to fairly good standard error estimates.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] However, Athreya has shown that if one performs a naive bootstrap on the sample mean when the underlying population lacks a finite variance (for example, a power law distribution), then the bootstrap distribution will not converge to the same limit as the sample mean.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] As a result, confidence intervals on the basis of a Monte Carlo simulation of the bootstrap could be misleading.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] Athreya states that "Unless one is reasonably sure that the underlying distribution is not heavy tailed, one should hesitate to use the naive bootstrap".
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] In univariate problems, it is usually acceptable to resample the individual observations with replacement ("case resampling" below) unlike subsampling, in which resampling is without replacement and is valid under much weaker conditions compared to the bootstrap.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] In small samples, a parametric bootstrap approach might be preferred.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] For other problems, a *smooth bootstrap* will likely be preferred.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] For regression problems, various other alternatives are available.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] The bootstrap is generally useful for estimating the distribution of a statistic (e.g. mean, variance) without using normality assumptions (as required, e.g., for a z-statistic or a t-statistic).
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] In particular, the bootstrap is useful when there is no analytical form or an asymptotic theory (e.g., an applicable central limit theorem) to help estimate the distribution of the statistics of interest.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] This is because bootstrap methods can apply to most random quantities, e.g., the ratio of variance and mean.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] There are at least two ways of performing case resampling.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] The 'exact' version for case resampling is similar, but we exhaustively enumerate every possible resample of the data set.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] This can be computationally expensive as there are a total of ${\binom {2n-1}{n}}={\frac {(2n-1)!}{n!(n-1)!}}$ different resamples, where *n* is the size of the data set.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] We flip the coin and record whether it lands heads or tails.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] Let *X = x*1, *x*2, …, *x*10 be 10 observations from the experiment.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] *xi* = 1 if the flip lands heads, and 0 otherwise.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] Such a normality assumption can be justified either as an approximation of the distribution of each *individual* coin flip or as an approximation of the distribution of the *average* of a large number of coin flips.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] The former is a poor approximation because the true distribution of the coin flips is Bernoulli instead of normal.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] The latter is a valid approximation in *infinitely large* samples due to the central limit theorem.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] However, if we are not ready to make such a justification, then we can use the bootstrap instead.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] Using case resampling, we can derive the distribution of ${\bar {x}}$ .
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] We first resample the data to obtain a *bootstrap resample*.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] There are some duplicates since a bootstrap resample comes from sampling with replacement from the data.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] Also the number of data points in a bootstrap resample is equal to the number of data points in our original observations.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] Then we compute the mean of this resample and obtain the first *bootstrap mean*: *μ*1*.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] We repeat this process to obtain the second resample *X*2* and compute the second bootstrap mean *μ*2*.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] This represents an *empirical bootstrap distribution* of sample mean.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] From this empirical distribution, one can derive a *bootstrap confidence interval* for the purpose of hypothesis testing.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] In regression problems, *case resampling* refers to the simple scheme of resampling individual cases – often rows of a data set.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] For regression problems, as long as the data set is fairly large, this simple scheme is often acceptable.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] However, the method is open to criticism.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] In regression problems, the explanatory variables are often fixed, or at least observed with more control than the response variable.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] Also, the range of the explanatory variables defines the information available from them.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] Therefore, to resample cases means that each bootstrap sample will lose some information.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] As such, alternative bootstrap procedures should be considered.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] Bootstrapping can be interpreted in a Bayesian framework using a scheme that creates new data sets through reweighting the initial data.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] Given a set of N data points, the weighting assigned to data point i in a new data set ${\mathcal {D}}^{J}$ is $w_{i}^{J}=x_{i}^{J}-x_{i-1}^{J}$ , where $\mathbf {x} ^{J}$ is a low-to-high ordered list of $N-1$ uniformly distributed random numbers on $[0,1]$ , preceded by 0 and succeeded by 1.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] The distributions of a parameter inferred from considering many such data sets ${\mathcal {D}}^{J}$ are then interpretable as posterior distributions on that parameter.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] Under this scheme, a small amount of (usually normally distributed) zero-centered random noise is added onto each resampled observation.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] This is equivalent to sampling from a kernel density estimate of the data.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] Assume *K* to be a symmetric kernel density function with unit variance.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] Based on the assumption that the original data set is a realization of a random sample from a distribution of a specific parametric type, in this case a parametric model is fitted by parameter θ, often by maximum likelihood, and samples of random numbers are drawn from this fitted model.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] Usually the sample drawn has the same sample size as the original data.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] Then the estimate of original function F can be written as ${\hat {F}}=F_{\hat {\theta }}$ .
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] This sampling process is repeated many times as for other bootstrap methods.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] The use of a parametric model at the sampling stage of the bootstrap methodology leads to procedures which are different from those obtained by applying basic statistical theory to inference for the same model.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] Another approach to bootstrapping in regression problems is to resample residuals.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] For each pair, (*xi*, *yi*), in which *xi* is the (possibly multivariate) explanatory variable, add a randomly resampled residual, ${\widehat {\varepsilon \,}}_{j}$ , to the fitted value ${\widehat {y\,}}_{i}$ .
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] In other words, create synthetic response variables $y_{i}^{*}={\widehat {y\,}}_{i}+{\widehat {\varepsilon \,}}_{j}$ where *j* is selected randomly from the list (1, ..., *n*) for every *i*.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] Refit the model using the fictitious response variables $y_{i}^{*}$ , and retain the quantities of interest (often the parameters, ${\widehat {\mu }}_{i}^{*}$ , estimated from the synthetic $y_{i}^{*}$ ).
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] Repeat steps 2 and 3 a large number of times.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] This scheme has the advantage that it retains the information in the explanatory variables.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] However, a question arises as to which residuals to resample.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] Raw residuals are one option; another is studentized residuals (in linear regression).
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] Although there are arguments in favor of using studentized residuals; in practice, it often makes little difference, and it is easy to compare the results of both schemes.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] When data are temporally correlated, straightforward bootstrapping destroys the inherent correlations.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] This method uses Gaussian process regression (GPR) to fit a probabilistic model from which replicates may then be drawn.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] GPR is a Bayesian non-linear regression method.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] A Gaussian process (GP) is a collection of random variables, any finite number of which have a joint Gaussian (normal) distribution.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] A GP is defined by a mean function and a covariance function, which specify the mean vectors and covariance matrices for each finite collection of the random variables.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] According to the equations above, the outputs *y* are also jointly distributed according to a multivariate Gaussian.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] The wild bootstrap, proposed originally by Wu (1986), is suited when the model exhibits heteroskedasticity.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] The idea is, as the residual bootstrap, to leave the regressors at their sample value, but to resample the response variable based on the residuals values.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] so the residuals are randomly multiplied by a random variable $v_{i}$ with mean 0 and variance 1.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] For most distributions of $v_{i}$ (but not Mammen's), this method assumes that the 'true' residual distribution is symmetric and can offer advantages over simple residual sampling for smaller sample sizes.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] The block bootstrap is used when the data, or the errors in a model, are correlated.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] In this case, a simple case or residual resampling will fail, as it is not able to replicate the correlation in the data.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] The block bootstrap tries to replicate the correlation by resampling inside blocks of data (see Blocking (statistics)).
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] The block bootstrap has been used mainly with data correlated in time (i.e. time series) but can also be used with data correlated in space, or among groups (so-called cluster data).
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] In the (simple) block bootstrap, the variable of interest is split into non-overlapping blocks.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] In the moving block bootstrap, introduced by Künsch (1989), data is split into *n* − *b* + 1 overlapping blocks of length *b*: Observation 1 to b will be block 1, observation 2 to *b* + 1 will be block 2, etc.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] Then from these *n* − *b* + 1 blocks, *n*/*b* blocks will be drawn at random with replacement.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] Then aligning these n/b blocks in the order they were picked, will give the bootstrap observations.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] This bootstrap works with dependent data, however, the bootstrapped observations will not be stationary anymore by construction.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] But, it was shown that varying randomly the block length can avoid this problem.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] This method is known as the *stationary bootstrap.* Other related modifications of the moving block bootstrap are the *Markovian bootstrap* and a stationary bootstrap method that matches subsequent blocks based on standard deviation matching.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] Vinod (2006), presents a method that bootstraps time series data using maximum entropy principles satisfying the Ergodic theorem with mean-preserving and mass-preserving constraints.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] There is an R package, **meboot**, that utilizes the method, which has applications in econometrics and computer science.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] Cluster data describes data where many observations per unit are observed.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] This could be observing many firms in many states or observing students in many classes.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] In such cases, the correlation structure is simplified, and one does usually make the assumption that data is correlated within a group/cluster, but independent between groups/clusters.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] The structure of the block bootstrap is easily obtained (where the block just corresponds to the group), and usually only the groups are resampled, while the observations within the groups are left unchanged.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] (2008) discusses this for clustered errors in linear regression.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] The bootstrap is a powerful technique although may require substantial computing resources in both time and memory.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] Some techniques have been developed to reduce this burden.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] They can generally be combined with many of the different types of Bootstrap schemes and various choices of statistics.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] Most bootstrap methods are embarrassingly parallel algorithms.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] That is, the statistic of interest for each bootstrap sample does not depend on other bootstrap samples.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] Such computations can therefore be performed on separate CPUs or compute nodes with the results from the separate nodes eventually aggregated for final analysis.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] The nonparametric bootstrap samples items from a list of size n with counts drawn from a multinomial distribution.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] If $W_{i}$ denotes the number times element i is included in a given bootstrap sample, then each $W_{i}$ is distributed as a binomial distribution with n trials and mean 1, but $W_{i}$ is not independent of $W_{j}$ for $i\neq j$ .
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] The Poisson bootstrap instead draws samples assuming all $W_{i}$ 's are independently and identically distributed as Poisson variables with mean 1.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] The Poisson bootstrap had been proposed by Hanley and MacGibbon as potentially useful for non-statisticians using software like SAS and SPSS, which lacked the bootstrap packages of R and S-Plus programming languages.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] The same authors report that for large enough n, the results are relatively similar to the nonparametric bootstrap estimates but go on to note the Poisson bootstrap has seen minimal use in applications.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] Another proposed advantage of the Poisson bootstrap is the independence of the $W_{i}$ makes the method easier to apply for large datasets that must be processed as streams.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] A way to improve on the Poisson bootstrap, termed "sequential bootstrap", is by taking the first samples so that the proportion of unique values is ≈0.632 of the original sample size n.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] This provides a distribution with main empirical characteristics being within a distance of $O(n^{3/4})$ .
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] Empirical investigation has shown this method can yield good results.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] This is related to the reduced bootstrap method.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] For massive data sets, it is often computationally prohibitive to hold all the sample data in memory and resample from the sample data.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] The Bag of Little Bootstraps (BLB) provides a method of pre-aggregating data before bootstrapping to reduce computational constraints.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] This works by partitioning the data set into b equal-sized buckets and aggregating the data within each bucket.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] This pre-aggregated data set becomes the new sample data over which to draw samples with replacement.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] This method is similar to the Block Bootstrap, but the motivations and definitions of the blocks are very different.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] Under certain assumptions, the sample distribution should approximate the full bootstrapped scenario.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] One constraint is the number of buckets $b=n^{\gamma }$ where $\gamma \in [0.5,1]$ and the authors recommend usage of $b=n^{0.7}$ as a general solution.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] The bootstrap distribution of a point estimator of a population parameter has been used to produce a bootstrapped confidence interval for the parameter's true value if the parameter can be written as a function of the population's distribution.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] Population parameters are estimated with many point estimators.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] Popular families of point-estimators include mean-unbiased minimum-variance estimators, median-unbiased estimators, Bayesian estimators (for example, the posterior distribution's mode, median, mean), and maximum-likelihood estimators.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] A Bayesian point estimator and a maximum-likelihood estimator have good performance when the sample size is infinite, according to asymptotic theory.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] For practical problems with finite samples, other estimators may be preferable.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] Asymptotic theory suggests techniques that often improve the performance of bootstrapped estimators; the bootstrapping of a maximum-likelihood estimator may often be improved using transformations related to pivotal quantities.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] The bootstrap distribution of a parameter-estimator is often used to calculate confidence intervals for its population-parameter.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] A variety of methods for constructing the confidence intervals have been proposed, although there is disagreement which method is the best.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] The survey of bootstrap confidence interval methods of DiCiccio and Efron and consequent discussion lists several desired properties of confidence intervals, which generally are not all simultaneously met.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] This method can be applied to any statistic.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] and where the sample statistic is median-unbiased and has maximum concentration (or minimum risk with respect to an absolute value loss function).
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] So that with a sample of 20 points, 90% confidence interval will include the true variance only 78% of the time.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] but they are less accurate in general than percentile confidence intervals, and some authors discourage their use.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] is the estimated standard error of the coefficient in the original model.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] as the t-test follows asymptotically a N(0,1) distribution), unlike the percentile bootstrap.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] Efron and Tibshirani suggest the following algorithm for comparing the means of two independent samples: Let $x_{1},\ldots ,x_{n}$ be a random sample from distribution F with sample mean ${\bar {x}}$ and sample variance $\sigma _{x}^{2}$ .
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] Draw a random sample ( $x_{i}^{*}$ ) of size n with replacement from $x_{i}'$ and another random sample ( $y_{i}^{*}$ ) of size m with replacement from $y_{i}'$ .
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] Repeat 3 and 4 B times (e.g. $B=1000$ ) to collect B values of the test statistic.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] In 1878, Simon Newcomb took observations on the speed of light.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] The data set contains two outliers, which greatly influence the sample mean.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] (The sample mean need not be a consistent estimator for any population mean, because no mean needs to exist for a heavy-tailed distribution.) A well-defined and robust statistic for the central tendency is the sample median, which is consistent and median-unbiased for the population median.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] The bootstrap distribution for Newcomb's data appears below.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] We can reduce the discreteness of the bootstrap distribution by adding a small amount of random noise to each bootstrap sample.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] A conventional choice is to add noise with a standard deviation of $\sigma /{\sqrt {n}}$ for a sample size *n*; this noise is often drawn from a Student-t distribution with *n-1* degrees of freedom.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] This results in an approximately-unbiased estimator for the variance of the sample mean.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] This means that samples taken from the bootstrap distribution will have a variance which is, on average, equal to the variance of the total population.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] Histograms of the bootstrap distribution and the smooth bootstrap distribution appear below.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] The bootstrap distribution of the sample-median has only a small number of values.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] The smoothed bootstrap distribution has a richer support.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] However, note that whether the smoothed or standard bootstrap procedure is favorable is case-by-case and is shown to depend on both the underlying distribution function and on the quantity being estimated.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] In this example, the bootstrapped 95% (percentile) confidence-interval for the population median is (26, 28.5), which is close to the interval for (25.98, 28.46) for the smoothed bootstrap.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] Bootstrap aggregating (bagging) is a meta-algorithm based on averaging model predictions obtained from models trained on multiple bootstrap samples.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] In situations where an obvious statistic can be devised to measure a required characteristic using only a small number, *r*, of data items, a corresponding statistic based on the entire sample can be formulated.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] Given an *r*-sample statistic, one can create an *n*-sample statistic by something similar to bootstrapping (taking the average of the statistic over all subsamples of size *r*).
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] This procedure is known to have certain good properties and the result is a U-statistic.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] The sample mean and sample variance are of this form, for *r* = 1 and *r* = 2.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] The bootstrap has under certain conditions desirable asymptotic properties.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] The asymptotic properties most often described are weak convergence / consistency of the sample paths of the bootstrap empirical process and the validity of confidence intervals derived from the bootstrap.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] This section describes the convergence of the empirical bootstrap.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] This paragraph summarizes more complete descriptions of stochastic convergence in van der Vaart and Wellner and Kosorok.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] The bootstrap defines a stochastic process, a collection of random variables indexed by some set T , where T is typically the real line ( $\mathbb {R}$ ) or a family of functions.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] Processes of interest are those with bounded sample paths, i.e., sample paths in L-infinity ( $\ell ^{\infty }(T)$ ), the set of all uniformly bounded functions from T to $\mathbb {R}$ .
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] This is because $C[0,1]$ contains the distribution functions for all continuous random variables, and $D[0,1]$ contains the distribution functions for all random variables.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] Statements about the consistency of the bootstrap are statements about the convergence of the sample paths of the bootstrap process as random elements of the metric space $\ell ^{\infty }(T)$ or some subspace thereof, especially $C[0,1]$ or $D[0,1]$ .
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] This is sometimes more specifically called **consistency relative to the Kolmogorov-Smirnov distance**.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] Horowitz goes on to recommend using a theorem from Mammen that provides easier to check necessary and sufficient conditions for consistency for statistics of a certain common form.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] In particular, let $\{X_{i}:i=1,\ldots ,n\}$ be the random sample.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] Convergence in (outer) probability as described above is also called **weak consistency**.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] It can also be shown with slightly stronger assumptions, that the bootstrap is **strongly consistent**, where convergence in (outer) probability is replaced by convergence (outer) almost surely.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] When only one type of consistency is described, it is typically weak consistency.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] This is adequate for most statistical applications since it implies confidence bands derived from the bootstrap are asymptotically valid.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] In simpler cases, it is possible to use the central limit theorem directly to show the consistency of the bootstrap procedure for estimating the distribution of the sample mean.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] Specifically, let us consider $X_{n1},\ldots ,X_{nn}$ independent identically distributed random variables with $\mathbb {E} [X_{n1}]=\mu$ and ${\text{Var}}[X_{n1}]=\sigma ^{2}<\infty$ for each $n\geq 1$ .
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] In addition, for each $n\geq 1$ , conditional on $X_{n1},\ldots ,X_{nn}$ , let $X_{n1}^{*},\ldots ,X_{nn}^{*}$ be independent random variables with distribution equal to the empirical distribution of $X_{n1},\ldots ,X_{nn}$ .
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] This is the sequence of bootstrap samples.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] To see this, note that $(X_{ni}^{*}-{\bar {X}}_{n})/{\sqrt {n}}{\hat {\sigma }}_{n}$ satisfies the Lindeberg condition, so the CLT holds.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] The Glivenko–Cantelli theorem provides theoretical background for the bootstrap method.
[src:jackknife-resampling/bootstrapping-statistics] Finite populations and drawing without replacement require adaptations of the bootstrap due to the violation of the i.i.d assumption.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] In statistics, an **estimator** is a rule for calculating an estimate of a given quantity based on observed data: thus the rule (the estimator), the quantity of interest (the estimand) and its result (the estimate) are distinguished.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] For example, the sample mean is a commonly used estimator of the population mean.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] There are point and interval estimators.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] The point estimators yield single-valued results.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] This is in contrast to an interval estimator, where the result would be a range of plausible values.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] "Single value" does not necessarily mean "single number", but includes vector valued or function valued estimators.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] An "estimator" or "point estimate" is a statistic (that is, a function of the data) that is used to infer the value of an unknown parameter in a statistical model.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] A common way of phrasing it is "the estimator is the method selected to obtain an estimate of an unknown parameter".
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] The parameter being estimated is sometimes called the *estimand*.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] It can be either finite-dimensional (in parametric and semi-parametric models), or infinite-dimensional (semi-parametric and non-parametric models).
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] If the parameter is denoted $\theta$ then the estimator is traditionally written by adding a circumflex over the symbol: ${\widehat {\theta }}$ .
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] Being a function of the data, the estimator is itself a random variable; a particular realization of this random variable is called the "estimate".
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] Sometimes the words "estimator" and "estimate" are used interchangeably.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] The definition places virtually no restrictions on which functions of the data can be called the "estimators".
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] The attractiveness of different estimators can be judged by looking at their properties, such as unbiasedness, mean square error, consistency, asymptotic distribution, etc.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] The construction and comparison of estimators are the subjects of the estimation theory.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] In the context of decision theory, an estimator is a type of decision rule, and its performance may be evaluated through the use of loss functions.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] When the word "estimator" is used without a qualifier, it usually refers to point estimation.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] The estimate in this case is a single point in the parameter space.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] There also exists another type of estimator: interval estimators, where the estimates are subsets of the parameter space.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] The problem of density estimation arises in two applications.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] Firstly, in estimating the probability density functions of random variables and secondly in estimating the spectral density function of a time series.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] In these problems the estimates are functions that can be thought of as point estimates in an infinite dimensional space, and there are corresponding interval estimation problems.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] Suppose a fixed *parameter* $\theta$ needs to be estimated.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] Then an "estimator" is a function that maps the sample space to a set of *sample estimates*.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] An estimator of $\theta$ is usually denoted by the symbol ${\widehat {\theta }}$ .
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] It is often convenient to express the theory using the algebra of random variables: thus if X is used to denote a random variable corresponding to the observed data, the estimator (itself treated as a random variable) is symbolised as a function of that random variable, ${\widehat {\theta }}(X)$ .
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] The estimate for a particular observed data value x (i.e. for $X=x$ ) is then ${\widehat {\theta }}(x)$ , which is a fixed value.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] Often an abbreviated notation is used in which ${\widehat {\theta }}$ is interpreted directly as a random variable, but this can cause confusion.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] The following definitions and attributes are relevant.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] For a given sample x , the "error" of the estimator ${\widehat {\theta }}$ is defined as $e(x)={\widehat {\theta }}(x)-\theta ,$ where $\theta$ is the parameter being estimated.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] The error, *e*, depends not only on the estimator (the estimation formula or procedure), but also on the sample.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] Suppose the parameter is the bull's-eye of a target, the estimator is the process of shooting arrows at the target, and the individual arrows are estimates (samples).
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] Then high MSE means the average distance of the arrows from the bull's eye is high, and low MSE means the average distance from the bull's eye is low.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] For example, even if all arrows hit the same point, yet grossly miss the target, the MSE is still relatively large.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] However, if the MSE is relatively low then the arrows are likely more highly clustered (than highly dispersed) around the target.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] The sampling deviation, d , depends not only on the estimator, but also on the sample.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] The variance of ${\widehat {\theta }}$ is the expected value of the squared sampling deviations; that is, $\operatorname {Var} ({\widehat {\theta }})=\operatorname {E} [({\widehat {\theta }}-\operatorname {E} [{\widehat {\theta }}])^{2}]$ .
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] It is used to indicate how far, on average, the collection of estimates are from the *expected value* of the estimates.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] (Note the difference between MSE and variance.) If the parameter is the bull's-eye of a target, and the arrows are estimates, then a relatively high variance means the arrows are dispersed, and a relatively low variance means the arrows are clustered.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] Even if the variance is low, the cluster of arrows may still be far off-target, and even if the variance is high, the diffuse collection of arrows may still be unbiased.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] Finally, even if all arrows grossly miss the target, if they nevertheless all hit the same point, the variance is zero.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] The bias of ${\widehat {\theta }}$ is defined as $B({\widehat {\theta }})=\operatorname {E} [{\widehat {\theta }}]-\theta$ .
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] It is the distance between the average of the collection of estimates, and the single parameter being estimated.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] The bias of ${\widehat {\theta }}$ is a function of the true value of $\theta$ so saying that the bias of ${\widehat {\theta }}$ is b means that for every $\theta$ the bias of ${\widehat {\theta }}$ is b .
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] There are two kinds of estimators: biased estimators and unbiased estimators.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] The bias is also the expected value of the error, since $\operatorname {E} [{\widehat {\theta }}]-\theta =\operatorname {E} [{\widehat {\theta }}-\theta ]$ .
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] If the parameter is the bull's eye of a target and the arrows are estimates, then a relatively high absolute value for the bias means the average position of the arrows is off-target, and a relatively low absolute bias means the average position of the arrows is on target.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] They may be dispersed, or may be clustered.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] The relationship between bias and variance is analogous to the relationship between accuracy and precision.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] The estimator ${\widehat {\theta }}$ is an unbiased estimator of $\theta$ if and only if $B({\widehat {\theta }})=0$ .
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] Bias is a property of the estimator, not of the estimate.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] Often, people refer to a "biased estimate" or an "unbiased estimate", but they really are talking about an "estimate from a biased estimator", or an "estimate from an unbiased estimator".
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] Also, people often confuse the "error" of a single estimate with the "bias" of an estimator.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] That the error for one estimate is large, does not mean the estimator is biased.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] In fact, even if all estimates have astronomical absolute values for their errors, if the expected value of the error is zero, the estimator is unbiased.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] Also, an estimator's being biased does not preclude the error of an estimate from being zero in a particular instance.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] The ideal situation is to have an unbiased estimator with low variance, and also try to limit the number of samples where the error is extreme (that is, to have few outliers).
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] Often, if just a little bias is permitted, then an estimator can be found with lower mean squared error and/or fewer outlier sample estimates.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] An alternative to the version of "unbiased" above, is "median-unbiased", where the median of the distribution of estimates agrees with the true value; thus, in the long run half the estimates will be too low and half too high.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] While this applies immediately only to scalar-valued estimators, it can be extended to any measure of central tendency of a distribution: see median-unbiased estimators.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] In a practical problem, ${\widehat {\theta }}$ can always have functional relationship with $\theta$ .
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] For example, if a genetic theory states there is a type of leaf (starchy green) that occurs with probability $p_{1}=1/4\cdot (\theta +2)$ , with $0<\theta <1$ .
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] Then, for n leaves, the random variable $N_{1}$ , or the number of starchy green leaves, can be modeled with a $\mathrm {Bin} (n,p_{1})$ distribution.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] The number can be used to express the following estimator for $\theta$ : ${\widehat {\theta }}=4/n\cdot N_{1}-2$ .
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] A desired property for estimators is the unbiased trait where an estimator is shown to have no systematic tendency to produce estimates larger or smaller than the true parameter.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] Additionally, unbiased estimators with smaller variances are preferred over larger variances because it will be closer to the "true" value of the parameter.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] The unbiased estimator with the smallest variance is known as the minimum-variance unbiased estimator (MVUE).
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] To find if an estimator ${\widehat {\theta }}$ is unbiased, it is easy to follow along the equation $\operatorname {E} [{\widehat {\theta }}]-\theta =0$ .
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] With estimator *T* with and parameter of interest $\theta$ solving the previous equation so it is shown as $\operatorname {E} [T]=\theta$ the estimator is unbiased.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] Looking at the figure to the right despite ${\hat {\theta }}_{2}$ being the only unbiased estimator, if the distributions overlapped and were both centered around $\theta$ then distribution ${\hat {\theta }}_{1}$ would actually be the preferred unbiased estimator.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] Note we are dividing by *n* − 1 because if we divided with *n* we would obtain an estimator with a negative bias which would thus produce estimates that are too small for $\sigma ^{2}$ .
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] It should also be mentioned that even though $S_{n}^{2}$ is unbiased for $\sigma ^{2}$ the reverse is not true.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] Below are illustrated the quantified properties of the estimation of the probability distribution mean, taking $\mu =0$ , $\sigma =1$ and $b=1/2$ .
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] in the case where the original distribution is normal and the estimator is the (biased) sample mean.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] In green is shown the histogram of 20000 estimates.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] The histogram converges to the exact distribution in the limit of infinite samples.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] ensures that the estimate distribution of the (biased) sample mean estimator also converges to the exact distribution in the limit of infinite sample size.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] A **consistent estimator** is an estimator whose sequence of estimates converge in probability to the quantity being estimated as the index (usually the sample size) grows without bound.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] In other words, increasing the sample size increases the probability of the estimator being close to the population parameter.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] The sequence is *strongly consistent*, if it converges almost surely to the true value.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] An estimator that converges to a *multiple* of a parameter can be made into a consistent estimator by multiplying the estimator by a scale factor, namely the true value divided by the asymptotic value of the estimator.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] This occurs frequently in estimation of scale parameters by measures of statistical dispersion.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] An estimator can be considered Fisher consistent as long as the estimator is the same functional of the empirical distribution function as the true distribution function.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] Following the formula: ${\widehat {\theta }}=h(T_{n}),\theta =h(T_{\theta })$ Where $T_{n}$ and $T_{\theta }$ are the empirical distribution function and theoretical distribution function, respectively.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] An easy example to see if some estimator is Fisher consistent is to check the consistency of mean and variance.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] For example, to check consistency for the mean ${\widehat {\mu }}={\bar {X}}$ and to check for variance confirm that ${\widehat {\sigma }}^{2}=SSD/n$ .
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] An asymptotically normal estimator is a consistent estimator whose distribution around the true parameter $\theta$ approaches a normal distribution with standard deviation shrinking in proportion to $1/{\sqrt {n}}$ as the sample size n grows.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] Using ${\xrightarrow {D}}$ to denote convergence in distribution, an estimator $t_{n}$ is asymptotically normal if ${\sqrt {n}}(t_{n}-\theta )\ \xrightarrow {D} \ N(0,V),$ for some V .
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] In this formulation $V/n$ can be called the *asymptotic variance* of the estimator.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] However, some authors also call V the *asymptotic variance*.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] Note that convergence will not necessarily have occurred for any finite n , therefore this value is only an approximation to the true variance of the estimator, while in the limit the asymptotic variance $V/n$ is simply zero.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] In particular, the distribution of the estimator $t_{n}$ converges weakly to a dirac delta function centered at $\theta$ .
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] Under mild conditions on the distribution of the data, the central limit theorem implies asymptotic normality of the sample mean ${\bar {X}}$ as an estimator of the true mean.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] More generally, maximum likelihood estimators are asymptotically normal under fairly weak regularity conditions — see the asymptotics section of the maximum likelihood article.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] However, not all estimators are asymptotically normal; the simplest examples are found when the true value of a parameter lies on the boundary of the allowable parameter region.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] The efficiency of an estimator is used to estimate the quantity of interest in a "minimum error" manner.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] In reality, there is not an explicit best estimator; there can only be a better estimator.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] These cannot in general both be satisfied simultaneously: a biased estimator may have a lower mean squared error than any unbiased estimator (see estimator bias).
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] The quality of the estimator can be identified from the comparison between the variance, the square of the estimator bias, or the MSE.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] The variance of the good estimator (good efficiency) would be smaller than the variance of the bad estimator (bad efficiency).
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] The square of an estimator bias with a good estimator would be smaller than the estimator bias with a bad estimator.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] The MSE of a good estimator would be smaller than the MSE of the bad estimator.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] Suppose there are two estimator, ${\widehat {\theta }}_{1}$ is the good estimator and ${\widehat {\theta }}_{2}$ is the bad estimator.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] If an estimator is efficient, in the frequency vs. value graph, there will be a curve with high frequency at the center and low frequency on the two sides.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] If an estimator is not efficient, the frequency vs. value graph, there will be a relatively more gentle curve.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] To put it simply, the good estimator has a narrow curve, while the bad estimator has a large curve.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] Plotting these two curves on one graph with a shared *y*-axis, the difference becomes more obvious.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] Among unbiased estimators, there often exists one with the lowest variance, called the minimum variance unbiased estimator (MVUE).
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] In some cases an unbiased efficient estimator exists, which, in addition to having the lowest variance among unbiased estimators, satisfies the Cramér–Rao bound, which is an absolute lower bound on variance for statistics of a variable.
[src:jackknife-resampling/estimator] Concerning such "best unbiased estimators", see also Cramér–Rao bound, Gauss–Markov theorem, Lehmann–Scheffé theorem, Rao–Blackwell theorem.
[src:jackknife-resampling/jackknife-resampling] In statistics, the **jackknife** (jackknife cross-validation) is a cross-validation technique and, therefore, a form of resampling.
[src:jackknife-resampling/jackknife-resampling] It is especially useful for bias and variance estimation.
[src:jackknife-resampling/jackknife-resampling] The jackknife pre-dates other common resampling methods such as the bootstrap.
[src:jackknife-resampling/jackknife-resampling] Given a sample of size n , a jackknife estimator can be built by aggregating the parameter estimates from each subsample of size $(n-1)$ obtained by omitting one observation.
[src:jackknife-resampling/jackknife-resampling] The jackknife is a linear approximation of the bootstrap.
[src:jackknife-resampling/jackknife-resampling] The jackknife technique was developed by Maurice Quenouille (1924–1973) from 1949 and refined in 1956.
[src:jackknife-resampling/jackknife-resampling] The jackknife estimator of a parameter is found by systematically leaving out each observation from a dataset and calculating the parameter estimate over the remaining observations and then aggregating these calculations.
[src:jackknife-resampling/jackknife-resampling] It could help to think that these n jackknife replicates ${\bar {x}}_{(1)},\ldots ,{\bar {x}}_{(n)}$ approximate the distribution of the sample mean ${\bar {x}}$ .
[src:jackknife-resampling/jackknife-resampling] One may ask about the bias and the variance of ${\bar {x}}_{\text{jack}}$ .
[src:jackknife-resampling/jackknife-resampling] From the definition of ${\bar {x}}_{\text{jack}}$ as the average of the jackknife replicates, one could try to calculate explicitly.
[src:jackknife-resampling/jackknife-resampling] The bias is a trivial calculation, but the variance of ${\bar {x}}_{\text{jack}}$ is more involved, since the jackknife replicates are not independent.
[src:jackknife-resampling/jackknife-resampling] For the special case of the mean, one can show explicitly that the jackknife estimate equals the usual estimate: ${\frac {1}{n}}\sum _{i=1}^{n}{\bar {x}}_{(i)}={\bar {x}}.$ This establishes the identity ${\bar {x}}_{\text{jack}}={\bar {x}}$ .
[src:jackknife-resampling/jackknife-resampling] However, these properties do not generally hold for parameters other than the mean.
[src:jackknife-resampling/jackknife-resampling] This simple example for the case of mean estimation is just to illustrate the construction of a jackknife estimator, while the real subtleties (and the usefulness) emerge for the case of estimating other parameters, such as higher moments than the mean or other functionals of the distribution.
[src:jackknife-resampling/jackknife-resampling] Then taking expectations, we get $E[{\widehat {\operatorname {var} }}({\bar {x}})_{\text{jack}}]=V[x]/n=V[{\bar {x}}]$ , so this is an unbiased estimator of the variance of ${\bar {x}}$ .
[src:jackknife-resampling/jackknife-resampling] The jackknife technique can be used to estimate (and correct) the bias of an estimator calculated over the entire sample.
[src:jackknife-resampling/jackknife-resampling] Suppose $\theta$ is the target parameter of interest, which is assumed to be some functional of the distribution of x .
[src:jackknife-resampling/jackknife-resampling] The value of ${\hat {\theta }}$ is sample-dependent, so this value will change from one random sample to another.
[src:jackknife-resampling/jackknife-resampling] In this kind of situation the jackknife resampling technique may be of help.
[src:jackknife-resampling/jackknife-resampling] This removes the bias in the special case that the bias is $O(n^{-1})$ and reduces it to $O(n^{-2})$ in other cases.
[src:jackknife-resampling/jackknife-resampling] The jackknife technique can be also used to estimate the variance of an estimator calculated over the entire sample.
[src:jackknife-resampling/resampling-statistics] In statistics, **resampling** is the creation of new samples based on one observed sample.
[src:jackknife-resampling/resampling-statistics] Permutation tests rely on resampling the original data assuming the null hypothesis.
[src:jackknife-resampling/resampling-statistics] Based on the resampled data it can be concluded how likely the original data is to occur under the null hypothesis.
[src:jackknife-resampling/resampling-statistics] It has been called the **plug-in principle**, as it is the method of estimation of functionals of a population distribution by evaluating the same functionals at the empirical distribution based on a sample.
[src:jackknife-resampling/resampling-statistics] For example, when estimating the population mean, this method uses the sample mean; to estimate the population median, it uses the sample median; to estimate the population regression line, it uses the sample regression line.
[src:jackknife-resampling/resampling-statistics] It may also be used for constructing hypothesis tests.
[src:jackknife-resampling/resampling-statistics] It is often used as a robust alternative to inference based on parametric assumptions when those assumptions are in doubt, or where parametric inference is impossible or requires very complicated formulas for the calculation of standard errors.
[src:jackknife-resampling/resampling-statistics] Bootstrapping techniques are also used in the updating-selection transitions of particle filters, genetic type algorithms and related resample/reconfiguration Monte Carlo methods used in computational physics.
[src:jackknife-resampling/resampling-statistics] In this context, the bootstrap is used to replace sequentially empirical weighted probability measures by empirical measures.
[src:jackknife-resampling/resampling-statistics] The bootstrap allows to replace the samples with low weights by copies of the samples with high weights.
[src:jackknife-resampling/resampling-statistics] Cross-validation is a statistical method for validating a predictive model.
[src:jackknife-resampling/resampling-statistics] Subsets of the data are held out for use as validating sets; a model is fit to the remaining data (a training set) and used to predict for the validation set.
[src:jackknife-resampling/resampling-statistics] Averaging the quality of the predictions across the validation sets yields an overall measure of prediction accuracy.
[src:jackknife-resampling/resampling-statistics] Cross-validation is employed repeatedly in building decision trees.
[src:jackknife-resampling/resampling-statistics] One form of cross-validation leaves out a single observation at a time; this is similar to the jackknife.
[src:jackknife-resampling/resampling-statistics] Another, *K*-fold cross-validation, splits the data into *K* subsets; each is held out in turn as the validation set.
[src:jackknife-resampling/resampling-statistics] For comparison, in regression analysis methods such as linear regression, each *y* value draws the regression line toward itself, making the prediction of that value appear more accurate than it really is.
[src:jackknife-resampling/resampling-statistics] Cross-validation applied to linear regression predicts the *y* value for each observation without using that observation.
[src:jackknife-resampling/resampling-statistics] This is often used for deciding how many predictor variables to use in regression.
[src:jackknife-resampling/resampling-statistics] Without cross-validation, adding predictors always reduces the residual sum of squares (or possibly leaves it unchanged).
[src:jackknife-resampling/resampling-statistics] In contrast, the cross-validated mean-square error will tend to decrease if valuable predictors are added, but increase if worthless predictors are added.
[src:jackknife-resampling/resampling-statistics] Subsampling is an alternative method for approximating the sampling distribution of an estimator.
[src:jackknife-resampling/resampling-statistics] 2. resampling is done without replacement.
[src:jackknife-resampling/resampling-statistics] The advantage of subsampling is that it is valid under much weaker conditions compared to the bootstrap.
[src:jackknife-resampling/resampling-statistics] In particular, a set of sufficient conditions is that the rate of convergence of the estimator is known and that the limiting distribution is continuous.
[src:jackknife-resampling/resampling-statistics] In addition, the resample (or subsample) size must tend to infinity together with the sample size but at a smaller rate, so that their ratio converges to zero.
[src:jackknife-resampling/resampling-statistics] While subsampling was originally proposed for the case of independent and identically distributed (iid) data only, the methodology has been extended to cover time series data as well; in this case, one resamples blocks of subsequent data rather than individual data points.
[src:jackknife-resampling/resampling-statistics] There are many cases of applied interest where subsampling leads to valid inference whereas bootstrapping does not; for example, such cases include examples where the rate of convergence of the estimator is not the square root of the sample size or when the limiting distribution is non-normal.
[src:jackknife-resampling/resampling-statistics] When both subsampling and the bootstrap are consistent, the bootstrap is typically more accurate.
[src:jackknife-resampling/resampling-statistics] RANSAC is a popular algorithm using subsampling.
[src:jackknife-resampling/resampling-statistics] Jackknifing (jackknife cross-validation), is used in statistical inference to estimate the bias and standard error (variance) of a statistic, when a random sample of observations is used to calculate it.
[src:jackknife-resampling/resampling-statistics] Historically, this method preceded the invention of the bootstrap with Quenouille inventing this method in 1949 and Tukey extending it in 1958.
[src:jackknife-resampling/resampling-statistics] This method was foreshadowed by Mahalanobis who in 1946 suggested repeated estimates of the statistic of interest with half the sample chosen at random.
[src:jackknife-resampling/resampling-statistics] He coined the name 'interpenetrating samples' for this method.
[src:jackknife-resampling/resampling-statistics] Quenouille invented this method with the intention of reducing the bias of the sample estimate.
[src:jackknife-resampling/resampling-statistics] The basic idea behind the jackknife variance estimator lies in systematically recomputing the statistic estimate, leaving out one or more observations at a time from the sample set.
[src:jackknife-resampling/resampling-statistics] From this new set of replicates of the statistic, an estimate for the bias and an estimate for the variance of the statistic can be calculated.
[src:jackknife-resampling/resampling-statistics] Jackknife is equivalent to the random (subsampling) leave-one-out cross-validation, it only differs in the goal.
[src:jackknife-resampling/resampling-statistics] For many statistical parameters the jackknife estimate of variance tends asymptotically to the true value almost surely.
[src:jackknife-resampling/resampling-statistics] In technical terms one says that the jackknife estimate is consistent.
[src:jackknife-resampling/resampling-statistics] The jackknife is consistent for the sample means, sample variances, central and non-central t-statistics (with possibly non-normal populations), sample coefficient of variation, maximum likelihood estimators, least squares estimators, correlation coefficients and regression coefficients.
[src:jackknife-resampling/resampling-statistics] It is not consistent for the sample median.
[src:jackknife-resampling/resampling-statistics] In the case of a unimodal variate the ratio of the jackknife variance to the sample variance tends to be distributed as one half the square of a chi square distribution with two degrees of freedom.
[src:jackknife-resampling/resampling-statistics] Instead of using the jackknife to estimate the variance, it may instead be applied to the log of the variance.
[src:jackknife-resampling/resampling-statistics] This transformation may result in better estimates particularly when the distribution of the variance itself may be non normal.
[src:jackknife-resampling/resampling-statistics] The jackknife, like the original bootstrap, is dependent on the independence of the data.
[src:jackknife-resampling/resampling-statistics] Extensions of the jackknife to allow for dependence in the data have been proposed.
[src:jackknife-resampling/resampling-statistics] One such extension is the delete-a-group method used in association with Poisson sampling.
[src:jackknife-resampling/resampling-statistics] Both methods, the bootstrap and the jackknife, estimate the variability of a statistic from the variability of that statistic between subsamples, rather than from parametric assumptions.
[src:jackknife-resampling/resampling-statistics] For the more general jackknife, the delete-m observations jackknife, the bootstrap can be seen as a random approximation of it.
[src:jackknife-resampling/resampling-statistics] Both yield similar numerical results, which is why each can be seen as approximation to the other.
[src:jackknife-resampling/resampling-statistics] Although there are huge theoretical differences in their mathematical insights, the main practical difference for statistics users is that the bootstrap gives different results when repeated on the same data, whereas the jackknife gives exactly the same result each time.
[src:jackknife-resampling/resampling-statistics] Because of this, the jackknife is popular when the estimates need to be verified several times before publishing (e.g., official statistics agencies).
[src:jackknife-resampling/resampling-statistics] On the other hand, when this verification feature is not crucial and it is of interest not to have a number but just an idea of its distribution, the bootstrap is preferred (e.g., studies in physics, economics, biological sciences).
[src:jackknife-resampling/resampling-statistics] Whether to use the bootstrap or the jackknife may depend more on operational aspects than on statistical concerns of a survey.
[src:jackknife-resampling/resampling-statistics] The jackknife, originally used for bias reduction, is more of a specialized method and only estimates the variance of the point estimator.
[src:jackknife-resampling/resampling-statistics] This can be enough for basic statistical inference (e.g., hypothesis testing, confidence intervals).
[src:jackknife-resampling/resampling-statistics] The bootstrap, on the other hand, first estimates the whole distribution (of the point estimator) and then computes the variance from that.
[src:jackknife-resampling/resampling-statistics] While powerful and easy, this can become highly computationally intensive.
[src:jackknife-resampling/resampling-statistics] "The bootstrap can be applied to both variance and distribution estimation problems.
[src:jackknife-resampling/resampling-statistics] However, the bootstrap variance estimator is not as good as the jackknife or the balanced repeated replication (BRR) variance estimator in terms of the empirical results.
[src:jackknife-resampling/resampling-statistics] Furthermore, the bootstrap variance estimator usually requires more computations than the jackknife or the BRR.
[src:jackknife-resampling/resampling-statistics] There is a special consideration with the jackknife, particularly with the delete-1 observation jackknife.
[src:jackknife-resampling/resampling-statistics] It should only be used with smooth, differentiable statistics (e.g., totals, means, proportions, ratios, odd ratios, regression coefficients, etc.; not with medians or quantiles).
[src:jackknife-resampling/resampling-statistics] This could become a practical disadvantage.
[src:jackknife-resampling/resampling-statistics] This disadvantage is usually the argument favoring bootstrapping over jackknifing.
[src:jackknife-resampling/resampling-statistics] More general jackknifes than the delete-1, such as the delete-m jackknife or the delete-all-but-2 Hodges–Lehmann estimator, overcome this problem for the medians and quantiles by relaxing the smoothness requirements for consistent variance estimation.
[src:jackknife-resampling/resampling-statistics] Usually the jackknife is easier to apply to complex sampling schemes than the bootstrap.
[src:jackknife-resampling/resampling-statistics] Complex sampling schemes may involve stratification, multiple stages (clustering), varying sampling weights (non-response adjustments, calibration, post-stratification) and under unequal-probability sampling designs.
[src:jackknife-resampling/resampling-statistics] Theoretical aspects of both the bootstrap and the jackknife can be found in Shao and Tu (1995), whereas a basic introduction is accounted in Wolter (2007).
[src:jackknife-resampling/resampling-statistics] The bootstrap estimate of model prediction bias is more precise than jackknife estimates with linear models such as linear discriminant function or multiple regression.
[src:jackknife-resampling/standard-error] The **standard error** (**SE**) of a statistic (usually an estimator of a parameter, like the average or mean) is the standard deviation of its sampling distribution.
[src:jackknife-resampling/standard-error] The standard error is often used in calculations of confidence intervals.
[src:jackknife-resampling/standard-error] The sampling distribution of a mean is generated by repeated sampling from the same population and recording the sample mean per sample.
[src:jackknife-resampling/standard-error] This forms a distribution of different sample means, and this distribution has its own mean and variance.
[src:jackknife-resampling/standard-error] Mathematically, the variance of the sampling mean distribution obtained is equal to the variance of the population divided by the sample size.
[src:jackknife-resampling/standard-error] This is because as the sample size increases, sample means cluster more closely around the population mean.
[src:jackknife-resampling/standard-error] Therefore, the relationship between the standard error of the mean and the standard deviation is such that, for a given sample size, the standard error of the mean equals the standard deviation divided by the square root of the sample size.
[src:jackknife-resampling/standard-error] In other words, the standard error of the mean is a measure of the dispersion of sample means around the population mean.
[src:jackknife-resampling/standard-error] In regression analysis, the term "standard error" refers either to the square root of the reduced chi-squared statistic or the standard error for a particular regression coefficient (as used in, say, confidence intervals).
[src:jackknife-resampling/standard-error] Suppose a statistically independent sample of n observations $x_{1},x_{2},\ldots ,x_{n}$ is taken from a statistical population with a standard deviation of $\sigma$ (the standard deviation of the population).
[src:jackknife-resampling/standard-error] The standard deviation $\sigma$ of the population being sampled is seldom known.
[src:jackknife-resampling/standard-error] When the sample size is small, using the standard deviation of the sample instead of the true standard deviation of the population will tend to systematically underestimate the population standard deviation, and therefore also the standard error.
[src:jackknife-resampling/standard-error] With *n* = 2, the underestimate is about 25%, but for *n* = 6, the underestimate is only 5%.
[src:jackknife-resampling/standard-error] Gurland and Tripathi (1971) provide a correction and equation for this effect.
[src:jackknife-resampling/standard-error] Sokal and Rohlf (1981) give an equation of the correction factor for small samples of *n* < 20.
[src:jackknife-resampling/standard-error] See unbiased estimation of standard deviation for further discussion.
[src:jackknife-resampling/standard-error] The standard error on the mean may be derived from the variance of a sum of independent random variables, given the definition of variance and some properties thereof.
[src:jackknife-resampling/standard-error] where a propagation in variance is used in the 2nd equality.
[src:jackknife-resampling/standard-error] In other words, if there are a large number of observations per sampling ( ${\textstyle n}$ is high compared with the population variance ${\textstyle \sigma }$ ), then the calculated mean per sample ${\textstyle {\bar {x}}}$ is expected to be close to the population mean x .
[src:jackknife-resampling/standard-error] For correlated random variables, the sample variance needs to be computed according to the Markov chain central limit theorem.
[src:jackknife-resampling/standard-error] There are cases when a sample is taken without knowing, in advance, how many observations will be acceptable according to some criterion.
[src:jackknife-resampling/standard-error] In such cases, the sample size N is a random variable whose variation adds to the variation of X such that, $\operatorname {Var} (T)=\operatorname {E} (N)\operatorname {Var} (X)+\operatorname {Var} (N){\big (}\operatorname {E} (X){\big )}^{2}$ which follows from the law of total variance.
[src:jackknife-resampling/standard-error] If N has a *Poisson distribution*, then $\operatorname {E} (N)=\operatorname {Var} (N)$ with estimator $n=N$ .
[src:jackknife-resampling/standard-error] Hence the estimator of $\operatorname {Var} (T)$ becomes $nS_{X}^{2}+n{\bar {X}}^{2}$ , leading the following formula for standard error: $\operatorname {Standard~Error} ({\bar {X}})={\sqrt {\frac {S_{X}^{2}+{\bar {X}}^{2}}{n}}}$ (since the standard deviation is the square root of the variance).
[src:jackknife-resampling/standard-error] In many practical applications, the true value of *σ* is unknown.
[src:jackknife-resampling/standard-error] As a result, we need to use a distribution that takes into account that spread of possible *σ'*s.
[src:jackknife-resampling/standard-error] When the true underlying distribution is known to be Gaussian, although with unknown σ, then the resulting estimated distribution follows the Student t-distribution.
[src:jackknife-resampling/standard-error] The standard error is the standard deviation of the Student t-distribution.
[src:jackknife-resampling/standard-error] T-distributions are slightly different from Gaussian, and vary depending on the size of the sample.
[src:jackknife-resampling/standard-error] Small samples are somewhat more likely to underestimate the population standard deviation and have a mean that differs from the true population mean, and the Student t-distribution accounts for the probability of these events with somewhat heavier tails compared to a Gaussian.
[src:jackknife-resampling/standard-error] To estimate the standard error of a Student t-distribution it is sufficient to use the sample standard deviation "s" instead of *σ*, and we could use this value to calculate confidence intervals.
[src:jackknife-resampling/standard-error] An example of how $\operatorname {SE}$ (Standard Error) is used to make confidence intervals of the unknown population mean is shown.
[src:jackknife-resampling/standard-error] If the sampling distribution is normally distributed, the sample mean, the standard error, and the quantiles of the normal distribution can be used to calculate confidence intervals for the true population mean.
[src:jackknife-resampling/standard-error] In particular, the standard error of a sample statistic (such as sample mean) is the actual or estimated standard deviation of the sample mean in the process by which it was generated.
[src:jackknife-resampling/standard-error] In other words, it is the actual or estimated standard deviation of the sampling distribution of the sample statistic.
[src:jackknife-resampling/standard-error] The notation for standard error can be any one of SE, SEM (for standard error of *measurement* or *mean*), or SE.
[src:jackknife-resampling/standard-error] In scientific and technical literature, experimental data are often summarized either using the mean and standard deviation of the sample data or the mean with the standard error.
[src:jackknife-resampling/standard-error] This often leads to confusion about their interchangeability.
[src:jackknife-resampling/standard-error] However, the mean and standard deviation are descriptive statistics, whereas the standard error of the mean is descriptive of the random sampling process.
[src:jackknife-resampling/standard-error] The standard deviation of the sample data is a description of the variation in measurements, while the standard error of the mean is a probabilistic statement about how the sample size will provide a better bound on estimates of the population mean, in light of the central limit theorem.
[src:jackknife-resampling/standard-error] Put simply, the **standard error** of the sample mean is an estimate of how far the sample mean is likely to be from the population mean, whereas the **standard deviation** of the sample is the degree to which individuals within the sample differ from the sample mean.
[src:jackknife-resampling/standard-error] The formula given above for the standard error assumes that the population is infinite.
[src:jackknife-resampling/standard-error] Nonetheless, it is often used for finite populations when people are interested in measuring the process that created the existing finite population (this is called an analytic study).
[src:jackknife-resampling/standard-error] Though the above formula is not exactly correct when the population is finite, the difference between the finite- and infinite-population versions will be small when sampling fraction is small (e.g. a small proportion of a finite population is studied).
[src:jackknife-resampling/standard-error] In this case people often do not correct for the finite population, essentially treating it as an "approximately infinite" population.
[src:jackknife-resampling/standard-error] If one is interested in measuring an existing finite population that will not change over time, then it is necessary to adjust for the population size (called an enumerative study).
[src:jackknife-resampling/standard-error] The effect of the FPC is that the error becomes zero when the sample size *n* is equal to the population size *N*.
[src:jackknife-resampling/standard-error] This happens in survey methodology when sampling without replacement.
[src:jackknife-resampling/standard-error] If sampling with replacement, then FPC does not come into play.
[src:jackknife-resampling/standard-error] This approximate formula is for moderate to large sample sizes; the reference gives the exact formulas for any sample size, and can be applied to heavily autocorrelated time series like Wall Street stock quotes.
[src:jackknife-resampling/standard-error] Moreover, this formula works for positive and negative ρ alike.
[src:jackknife-resampling/standard-error] See also unbiased estimation of standard deviation for more discussion.
